
╔═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
║  MISSION: TRANSMISSION FILTERING                                          ║
║  SKILL: Pipes, head, tail, sort, uniq                                     ║
╚═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

OBJECTIVE:
The transmission buffer contains hundreds of signal fragments. Most are
noise, but hidden among them are message fragments from Earth. You need
to filter out the noise and identify the unique signal sources.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

TASK: Identify the Earth Transmission
─────────────────────────────────────
The file 'signal_buffer.txt' contains mixed transmissions from various
sources. Each line has the format:

    SOURCE:SIGNAL_STRENGTH:MESSAGE

Your tasks:
1. Find all unique signal SOURCES (first field)
2. Identify which source is from EARTH
3. Count how many transmissions came from Earth

The answer is the NUMBER of Earth transmissions.

When you have the count, run:
    ./verify <count>

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

USEFUL COMMANDS:
    cat signal_buffer.txt                      View all signals
    head -20 signal_buffer.txt                 See first 20 lines
    cut -d':' -f1 signal_buffer.txt            Extract sources
    cut -d':' -f1 file | sort | uniq           Unique sources
    grep "EARTH" signal_buffer.txt             Find Earth signals
    grep "EARTH" signal_buffer.txt | wc -l     Count Earth signals

PIPELINE EXAMPLE:
    cat file | cut -d':' -f1 | sort | uniq

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

